LAB 5¶

Introduction¶

In this project we are going to look at an inclusive search for the standard model Higgs boson in pp collisions at √ s = 13 TeV at the LHC using simulated data. The Higgs bosons are produced with large transverse momentum (pT) and decaying to a bottom quark-antiquark pair. The Higgs candidates could be reconstructed as large-radius jets using Calorimeters. Due to large QCD backgorund containmination, the direct 5-sigma observation of this Higgs channel is not accomplished yet. We are going to use a set of training datasets to optimize event selections in order to enhance the discovery sensitivity. The optimal event selections will be applied to a selected pseudo-experiment data.

About the Experimental Data¶

The LHC produces around 1 billion events per second which is comparable to the speed of a CPU in a computer. This is great as it means that the computer can process the events - just barely - however the storage required to record an event is around 1 MB which, for 1 billion events, is not feasible. Instead, about 200 MB of data is written per second thus only about 100 to 200 of the 1 billion events are recorded. In order to determine which data to write and which data to throw away a triggering system is put in place - informed by the physical event that is trying to be observed. This system will result in recording events that satisfy a list of criteria. We could imagine one possible criteria would be for the mass of the particle observed to be around $125 \ GeV/c^2$ if we were searching for the Higgs Boson.

Our data set not true data from the LHC ATLAS detector but rather simulated data. We have a total of 100k simulated QCD Background events and 100k Higgs Boson events. Additionally, the data set we will be exploring will only include events that have a high transverse momentum, $pT$, between 1000 and 1200. Provided this data is simulated, our expected yields in the lab are $N_{higgs} = 100$ and $N_{qcd} = 2000$.

We can see that both the qcd dataset and higgs data set have the same features the description of the features are given below:-¶

pt : pt is the transverse momentum.

eta : $\eta$ is the pseudorapidity which is a geometric property. The pseudorapidity is used to describe the angle of the particle relative to the beam axis. This value ranges from $-\infty$ to $\infty$ as the polar angle $\theta$ goes from $0$ to $\pi$.

phi : $\phi$ is the azimuthal angle and it goes around the beam.

mass : is the mass of the particle produced via the collision.

ee2 : The 2-point energy correlation function. This energy correlation function is utilized for quark and gluon discrimination.

ee3 : The 3-point energy correlation function. This energy correlation function is utilized for boosted W / Z / Higgs Boson identification.

d2: $D_2$ is written in the following way where $E_{CFi}$ is the $i$-th energy correlation function: $D_2 = E_{CF3} * \big(\frac{E_{CF1}}{E_{CF2}}\big)^3$

angularity : Angularity is from the family of infrared-safe quantities that have characteristic distributions for two-body decays - the Higgs Boson.

t1 : t1 represents the 1-jettiness. This is the sum of the angular distance of each particle to the jet center.

t2 : t2 represents the 2-jettiness. This is the sum of the angular distance of each particle to that particle's respective jet center. With a jettiness of 2 we have two jet centers and our particles have been grouped into one or the other jet in order to minimize the value of t2.

t3 : t3 represents the 3-jettiness. This is the sum of the angular distance of each particle to that particle's respective jet center. With a jettiness of 3 we have three jet centers and our particles have been grouped into a jet in order to minimize the value of t3.

t21 : t21 is the ratio t2/t1 This captures how much of an improvement we made by grouping the particles with two jets instead of one.

t32 : t32 is the ratio t3/t2. This captures how much of an improvement we made by grouping the particles with three jets instead of two.

KtDeltaR: $k_t \Delta R$ is the $\Delta R$ of two subjects within a large-R jet. This is describing the algorithm that is being used to determine the jet centers for the particles - or the clustering algorithm.

plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (5,5)

def plot_feature(feature):
    
    
    # plot the background
    #plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    plt.hist(qcd_data[f'{feature}'], label = 'background')
    plt.title(f'{feature}' + '  Higgs Boson Signal /' + 'QCD Background')
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Event counts')

    # plot the signal
    #plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
    plt.hist(higgs_data[f'{feature}'], label = 'signal')
    #plt.title('Higgs Boson Signal')
    
    plt.xlabel(f' {feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Event counts')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

The following features provide discrimination power between signal and background:¶

pt, eta, ee2, ee3, d2, t2, t3, t21, KDeltaR, mass, angularity

The following features do not provide discrimination power between signal and background¶

phi,t32

The following features do provide discrimination power, however the discrimination is not large¶

t1

Exploring the correlations in data¶

we know that $D_2 = E_{CF3} * \big(\frac{E_{CF1}}{E_{CF2}}\big)^3$ thus we can say that d2 is correlated to ee2, ee3 and ee1

This can be seen in the data also as d2, ee2,ee3 and ee1 provide discrimination power also the plot for d2 is quite similar to ee3

we know that t21 = t2/t1, the plots of t21 and t2 are pretty similar in the sense that both the higg data and qcd data have diferent means and have the same range of data and t1 is similar but does not provide too much discrimination power

t32 = t3/t2,thus we know that t32 is correlated to t3 and t2. The plot for t32 does not provide much discrimination power however, the plot for t3 and t2 do, its difficult to find the correlation for these using the plots

Expected Discovery Sensitivity¶

Expected yields of higgs events Nhiggs=100, Expected yields of background events Nqcd=20000

The background distribution is a poisson distribution with a mean of 20000 events to find the significance of our signal we need to find the significance of (Nhiggs + Nqcd) 20100 events.

In [60]:
prob = stats.poisson.sf(20100, 20000)
sig = stats.norm.ppf(prob)
sig
Out[60]:
-0.7112259282313185

Thus the significance of finding our signal is .7112259282313185

Develop a plan to optimize the discovery sensitivity by applying selections to these features.¶

The significance is not high enough to confirm our signal, the significance required to confirm our signal is 5.

Thus, we need to develop a plan to optimize the discovery sensitivity by applying selections to these features.

Narrowing down the background based on ee3 will be good choice as the mean of the signal and the background for the histogram of this feature is the same and the width of the histogram for the signal is smaller than the background

We will remove all the data that has ee3 greater than 0.022

In [61]:
cut_qcd = qcd_data[(qcd_data['ee3'] < .022)]
cut_higgs = higgs_data[(higgs_data['ee3'] < .022)]
